Lecture 7 - Generalized Linear Model

Generalized Linear Model

Generalized linear models are extensions of traditional regression models that allow the mean to depend on the explanatory variables through a link function, and the response variable to be any member of a set of distributions called the exponential family (e.g., Normal, Poisson, Binomial). We can use the function glm() to work with generalized linear models in R.

  • Classical linear model: \(y=X\beta+\varepsilon\)
    • Random component: \(y_i \sim N(\mu_i,\sigma^2)\)
    • Systematic component: linear predictor \(\eta\) defined by \(\eta=\sum_{j=1}^px_j\beta_j\)
    • Link function: \(\mu=\eta\)

Extending above to: exponential family distribution for the random part, monotone differentiable link function for the systematic part.

  • Component of the GLM:
    • Systematic component: Identifies the set of explanatory variables
      • Linear predictor \(\eta=\sum_{j=1}^px_j\beta_j\)
      • Link function \(\eta=g(\mu)\), \(\mu=E(y)\)
    • Random component: Identifies dependent variable and its probability distribution \(y\sim\)exponential family
      • \(f(y,\theta,\phi)=exp\{(y\theta-b(\theta))/\phi+c(y,\phi)\}\)
      • Binary Responses -> Binomial Distribution
      • Count Responses -> Poisson Distribution (or Negative Binomial)
      • Positive and Skewed Responses -> Gamma Distribution
    • Link function: Identifies a function of the mean that is a linear function of the explanatory variables
      • log link: \(\eta=\log(\mu)\), \(\mu=e^\eta\)
      • logit link: \(\eta=\log(\frac{\mu}{1-\mu})=logit(\mu)\), \(\mu=\frac{e^\eta}{1+e^\eta}\)

Logistic Regression

Logistic regression is appropriate when the response variable is categorical with two possible outcomes (i.e., binary outcomes). Binary variables can be represented using an indicator variable \(Y_i\), taking on values 0 or 1, and modeled using a binomial distribution with probability \(P(Y_i=1) = p_i\). Logistic regression models this probability as a function of one or more explanatory variables.

\(P(Y_i=1)=f(t)=\frac{e^{X\beta}}{1+e^{X\beta}}=logit^{-1}(X\beta)\),

\(logit(P_i)=\log(\frac{P_i}{1-P_i})=X\beta\)

odds: ratio of two probabilities \(\frac{p}{1-p}\)

Interpretation: e.g. every one unit increase in \(X_1\) = \(\beta_1\) increase log odds of y.

glm(response ~ explanantory_variables, family=binomial)
predict.glm(fit)

  • 勝算Odds \(\frac{p}{1-p}\) 發生與沒發生的比值

  • 勝算比Odds Ratio (OR) 兩個勝算相除

  • 邏輯斯迴歸的迴歸式 \(\log ( \text{odds} ) = \text{logit} (P) = \log \left( \frac{P(Y=1) }{1-P(Y=1)} \right) = X\beta\) 故 \(exp(\text{logit} (P))\) = 勝算

  • 可由勝算回推機率, 機率 = 勝算 / (1 + 勝算)=\(\frac{e^{X\beta}}{1+e^{X\beta}}\)

  • 白話文：“log(勝算) = log (p/(1 - p)) = 迴歸模型”，“勝算比 = 勝算1 / 勝算2”

Model Validation 表現如何

Confusion matrix

predict(model, new, type = "response"),

[Ref] https://www.ycc.idv.tw/confusion-matrix.html

Model selection

ROC curve

Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curves are a common
tool to diagnose the ability of a binary classifier

利用曲線下的面積(Area Under Curve; AUC)來判別分類器的鑑別力。以下為AUC數值的判別規則建議：

\(\text{AUC }=0.5\) (no discrimination)

\(0.7\leq \text{AUC }\leq 0.8\) (acceptable discrimination)

\(0.8\leq \text{AUC } \leq 0.9\) (excellent discrimination)

\(0.9\leq \text{AUC } \leq 1.0\) (outstanding discrimination)

library(InformationValue)

optimalCutoff(real, predicted) # find the best cutoff
confusionMatrix(real, predicted, threshold = 0.5)
misClassError(real, predicted, threshold = 0.5) # error rate
plotROC(real, predicted) #ROC curve
sensitivity(real, predicted, threshold = 0.5)
specificity(real, predicted, threshold = 0.5)

Another way:

library(pROC)
temp <- roc(real, predicted)
temp$auc
roc.data <- tibble(x = 1-temp$specificities, y = temp$sensitivities)
ggplot(roc.data, aes(x = x, y = y)) + 
geom_line() + 
ylab("Sensitivity") + 
xlab("1-Specificity")

Poisson Regression

Poisson regression models count variables that assumes poisson distribution. When the count variable is over dispersed, having to much variation, Negative Binomial regression is more suitable.

\(Y_i\sim Poisson(\mu)\),

\(\log(\mu)=X\beta\)

\(\mu=exp(X\beta)\)

Interpretation: e.g. \(Y_i\sim Poisson(exp(2.8+0.012X_1-0.2X_2))\)

for each 1 \(X_1\) increase is \(e^{0.012}=1.127\) or 12.7% increases in y. for each 1 \(X_2\) increase is \(e^{-0.2}=0.82\) or 18% decreases in y.

library (MASS)
Model <- glm(countResponse ~ x1 + x2, family="poisson", data=Data) 
summary(Model) 
predict(Model, newdata, type="response")

Note: rate 率

Poisson models handle exposure variables by using simple algebra to change the dependent variable from a rate into a count.

If the rate is count/exposure, the final model contains ln(exposure) as a term that is added to the regression coefficients. This logged variable, ln(exposure), is called the offset variable補償項. One important feature of an offset variable is that it is required to have a coefficient of 1. This is because it is part of the rate.

Under Poisson process, \(\mu=\lambda t\)

\(Y\sim Poisson(\lambda t)\),

\(\log(\lambda_i)=\log(\frac{\mu_i}{t_i})=X\beta\)

\(\log(\mu_i)-\log(t_i)=X\beta\)

\(\log(\mu_i)=\log(t_i)+X\beta\)

\(\log(t_i)\)is the offset 補償項 variable. 係數被強制為1

#兩種寫法皆可
glm(count ~ x1+x2, offset = log(XXX),family = poisson, data) 
glm(count ~ x1+x2 + offset(log(XXX)), family = poisson, data)

Sometimes there are many, many more zeros in Y, then need Zero Inflated Poisson Model

Overdispersion 過度離散

We would expect \(Var(y)=E(y)\), but often we find \(Var(y)>E(y)\).

can check by:

#quick chechk:  The rule of thumb is that the ratio of
deviance to df should be 1
summary(model)

library(qcc)
qcc.overdispersion.test(y, type = "poisson") #sig. means overdispersion

#or

library(AER)
dispersiontest(pmodel)

Overdispersion means the assumptions of the model are not met, hence we cannot trust its output, so fit other models, like quasipossion, negative binomial

配適結果 Goodness of fit test

If the residual deviance is close enough to the residual degrees of freedom, it is a good fit. It can be tested by Chi-squared test.

pchisq(deviance(pmodel), df.residual(pmodel), lower.tail=FALSE)

\(H_0: \text{ deviance} \sim \chi^2 \text{ distribution}\)

so reject \(H_0\) 表示 不符合卡方分配，可能有過度離散，不是一個好的配適結果。
